BEL Leroux Algorithm

The metropolis hastings algorithm to draw samples of fixed effect \(\beta\) and spatial random effects \(\psi\) are drawn from simulated data set. Some data are generated as follows:

Response \(y\) was generated for each of the 2147 small reas across Australia. the spatial information to calculate the neighbourhood matrix are available to us.

Checking the output keeping psi fixed

To check the algorithm performance, we are not sampling the spatial random effect, keeping it fixed to the initial value. For skipping the burnin and checking the algorithm, we have initialised betas to its true value (intercept= 7, slope = 14).

The results of the algorithm are as follows:

## [1] "intercept"
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   6.665   6.825   6.942   6.905   6.983   7.037
## [1] "slope"
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   13.95   14.05   14.12   14.20   14.35   14.68

## [1] "Precision paramter"
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## 0.02142 0.02902 0.03139 0.04830 0.03385 8.29524

So, the algorithm was able to estimate the true beta value. Now, we are changing the initial value of beta and taking an initial value from a multivariate normal prior.

Now, if we change the initial values of \(\beta\) from the true value to randomly generated values from prior distribution, the slope parameter can be estimated fine, but the intercept is not working well. That means there is still some bug in the algorithm that need fixing.

MCMC with 100,000 iteration, burnin = 50000

We ran same codes with initial psi set to true value and beta initial randomlt selected from a prior and ran 100,000 iterations. The results below shows that we still got problem in sampling the intercept as the intercept values are not even closer to the true value (7). The slope is working well, but it also performed well in case of 1000 or 10000 iteration. We need to fix this problem somehow to move forward.

## [1] "intercept"
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## -39.6241 -20.0160 -16.7282 -16.9644 -13.6791   0.4826
## [1] "slope"

Using Debugged codes

We have debugged the codes and now the algorithm can estimate the true values of intercept and slope even with a lower number of iterations. The results after 10000 iteration, burnin=1000 ( \(\psi\) still taking true value as initial and variance is known). The summary estimates look good as they are near the true values of regression coefficients. But since this is for a smaller number of iterations, the chain did not converge. We can run longer chains to see if they converge.

## [1] "intercept"
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  -1.666   5.827   7.330   7.152   8.045  12.067

Using Debugged codes and moving initial psi from true psi

We run the chain for 50000 iterations and also changed the initial psi to be 0 for each of the small area, following the algorithm in our paper and the Porter paper. The results are shown below. This one is really good in estimating. The only restrictions in place is, we are still assuming the variance to be knowd, taken as the variance of the true psi and we aer using fixed values of rho.

Using Debugged codes and estimating variance within the chains

We run the chain for 50000 iterations and also changed the initial psi to be 0 for each of the small area, following the algorithm in our paper and the Porter paper. The results are shown below. This one is really good in estimating. The only restrictions in place is, we are still assuming the variance to be knowd, taken as the variance of the true psi and we aer using fixed values of rho. The results look good. One last restriction to release in this algorithm is to estimate the spatial dependence paramter rho simultaneously.
